The most common way to indicate that an error has occurred in a C function is to return non-zero. If this is done consistently, and return values are always checked, an error condition will eventually make its way up to main, where you can fail gracefully.<p>For example:<p><pre><code>    int a(void)
    {
        ...
        if (oops) {
            return 1;
        }
        return 0;
    }

    int b(void)
    {
        if (a(...) != 0) {
            return 1;
        }
        return 0;
    }

    int main(void)
    {
        if (b(...) != 0) {
            exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
        }
        return EXIT_SUCCESS;
    }
</code></pre>
(This means that void functions should be avoided.)
